<section xml:id="sec-isom-reflect-Cartesian" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>An Introduction to Reflections</title>
<introduction>
<p>
    A <term>reflection</term> is the first transformation we will explore. 
    Each reflection is defined by a 
    mirror line and the reflection takes each point to its reflected image. If we were to fold the plane across
    the mirror line, the points and their images would fall on top of each other.
</p>
<p>
    As you begin this section, it can be advantageous to use paper and colored pencils, 
    printing out 
    <!--<xref ref="fig-reflectP"/>, <xref ref="fig-findline"/>, and
    <xref ref="fig-refl-across-both-axes"/>--> 
    <xref ref="fig-reflect-paperP"/> or carefully copying it onto 
    graph paper. Tactile tools will encourage us to use previous experience 
    and develop spacial skills, giving us a broader understanding of reflections
    and the Cartesian coordinate system. 
    In addition, working on paper allows us to check our work by folding.
</p>
<p>
    We will use GeoGebra tools for finding reflections in 
    <xref ref="sec-composing-reflections"/>. Although a GeoGebra interactive 
    is available for both <xref ref="draw-reflection"/> in the current 
    section are designed to mimic tasks you would do with paper and pencils
    and do not exploit the power of GeoGebra. In fact, in the interactive 
    version reflection tools have been turned off.
</p>

</introduction>
<subsection>
    <title>Exploring Reflections</title>
<exploration xml:id="expl-reflect-pentomino-coordplane">
    <title>
        Reflections in the Cartesian Coordinate Plane
    </title>
    <task xml:id="drawreflection">
    <statement>
        <p>
            In <xref ref="fig-reflect-paperP"/>, use the coordinate grid 
            to reflect pentomino <m>ABCDEF</m> across line 
            <m>\overleftrightarrow{GH}</m>, plotting the image of each vertex.
            Give the reflected image of <m>A</m> the label <m>A'</m>, the reflected 
            image of <m>B</m> the label <m>B'</m>.  
            Connect the vertices to form hexagon <m>A'B'C'D'E'F'</m>.
        </p>
        <aside>
            <p>
                The interactive <xref ref="fig-GGreflectP"/>, provided at the end 
                of the section and accessible using the link, attempts to mimic the 
                use of pencil and paper use the Plot Point tool. Plotting reflected points
